{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2638"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2638"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.3,0.11,0.04,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110665"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2638"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92912"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3816"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110665"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-week history of nausea, vomiting, and post-prandial abdominal distension. He reports no other gastrointestinal symptoms including no abdominal pain or bowel changes. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has had minimal contact with any healthcare setting over the past decade and has declined participation in any national population-based screening program.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination, including assessment of mucous membranes and abdominal examination are unremarkable. Abdominal CT scan reveals a tumour obstructing his proximal jejunum. He is referred urgently to general surgery for further evaluation. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following risk factors is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Familial adenomatous polyposis","Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","Coeliac disease","Ulcerative colitis","Crohn disease"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamilial adenomatous polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E (FAP) is the most likely risk factor present in this young patient to cause him to have an obstructing tumour in his small bowel. FAP is caused by an autosomal dominant mutation in the APC gene, which is a tumour suppressor gene located on chromosome 5q22. Patients with FAP typically develop polyposis (widespread bowel polyps) in their second or third decade of life, often remaining asymptomatic until progressing to colorectal cancer. This is consistent with the presentation of this patient. These patients can have up to thousands of colorectal adenomas and a 100% risk of colorectal cancer in their lives. Patients with FAP have an increased risk of developing small bowel cancer, with the lifetime risk being about 5%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeutz-Jeghers syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is another risk factor for developing colorectal cancer, due to an autosomal dominant mutation in the STK11 gene. These patients typically develop hyperpigmented macules around their lips, genitals, palms, soles, and buccal mucosa \u2013 making this diagnosis less likely than FAP, as the patient does not have any of these overt signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune disorder characterised by an intestinal hypersensitivity to gluten. A complication of this is a moderately increased risk of malignancies, such as enteropathy-associated T-cell lymphoma (EATL), often located in the proximal jejunum. .\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E causes an increased risk of colorectal cancer. However, it does not cause an increased risk of upper gastrointestinal tumours, as ulcerative colitis impacts the rectum and can extend in a proximal and continuous fashion to involve other parts of the colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn disease\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with increased risk of colorectal cancer. These patients are also at risk of developing small bowel tumours, but the tumours tend to be in the distal small bowel. In this case, the clinical presentation is not consistent with Crohn disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all of these conditions can increase the risk of various gastrointestinal cancers, FAP is most strongly associated with small bowel adenocarcinoma, particularly in the absence of other clinical signs or symptoms suggestive of the other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary small bowel tumours are an uncommon, but important cause of small bowel obstruction.","Familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) is associated with an increased risk of small bowel adenocarcinoma."],"references":["Green PHR, Fleischauer AT, Bhagat G, Goyal R, Jabri B, Neugut AI. Risk of malignancy in patients with celiac disease. The American Journal of Medicine. 2003;115(3):191\u20135. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12935825/","Syngal S, Brand RE, Church JM, Giardiello FM, Hampel HL, Burt RW. ACG Clinical Guideline: Genetic Testing and Management of Hereditary Gastrointestinal Cancer Syndromes. American Journal of Gastroenterology. 2015;110(2):223\u201362. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25645574/","Utsunomiya J, Gocho H, Miyanaga T. Peutz-Jeghers syndrome: its natural course and management. Johns Hopkins Med J. 1975;136(2):71. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1117595/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92912"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2638"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92912"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T19:49:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T19:51:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2638"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110665"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"it